I finished this book a few days ago and have still not stopped thinking about it. House of Hunger by Alexis Henderson delves into a world where youth and eternal life can be granted by the imbibing of blood. Special blood maids are hired by those in the North wealthy enough to afford them and these blood maids have only one job: to bleed for their master. Marion Shaw is running away from her life in the slums when she happens upon an advertisement looking to hire a new blood maid. When she passes the sanguine interview, she is whisked away to the luxury of the North to meet her new master: Countess Lisavet. The countess is alluring, powerful, and most of all, intimidating beyond belief. Will Marion be able to survive her indenture and retire with a wealth she could never have imagined or will she succumb to something so very dark and ancient? 🩸

 This book is everything I could ever want in a debaucherous house of blood lust. Marion Shaw is an incredibly relatable character who has some morally gray areas, yes, but in the end is only trying to survive. I was drooling as I read over her developing relationship with the countess and binged the second half of the book in one sitting. It’s a fast paced narrative with no room to breathe inducing euphoric claustrophobia. With spooky season here, if you’re looking for a book drowning in blood-lust, limned with the red tincture of gore, and indulgent of a love so forbidden, it must be hidden away in the dank tunnels of a gothic mansion, you must pick this book up and ravish its pages. Now. 📖🖤

@lexish , between this and The Year of the Witching, I will read everything you ever write from this moment on into eternity. 🩸🖤
